11:16.609 --> 11:18.377 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
by hard-liners.

11:18.411 --> 11:22.982 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
HASSAN ROUHANI, Iranian
President (through
translator): Iran and America,
over the last

11:23.015 --> 11:27.019 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
almost 40 years, have traveled a
curvy road
together.

11:27.053 --> 11:30.222 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We are waiting for the U.S.
government to
become stable intellectually.

11:30.256 --> 11:33.559 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I hope it can settle down so
that we can more
accurately pass judgments on
their leaders

11:33.592 --> 11:35.294 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
in Washington.

11:35.327 --> 11:39.131 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Also today,
Iranian reports
said that reformist supporters
of Rouhani

11:39.165 --> 11:45.304 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
swept all the local offices in
Tehran and
did well in other cities as
well.

11:45.337 --> 11:49.508 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Back in this country, the U.S.
Supreme Court
has struck down two North
Carolina congressional

11:49.542 --> 11:52.344 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
districts over racial
gerrymandering.

11:52.378 --> 11:58.284 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The ruling upheld a lower court
finding that
Republican state lawmakers
lumped black voters

11:58.317 --> 12:01.287 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
into the districts to weaken
their clout elsewhere.

12:01.320 --> 12:04.790 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The districts have already been
redrawn.

12:04.824 --> 12:10.362 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The state legislature in Texas
is nearing
approval of a transgender
bathroom bill similar

12:10.396 --> 12:14.066 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to North Carolina's measure that
sparked national
outrage.

12:14.100 --> 12:19.905 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The Texas bill limits children
in public and
charter schools to bathrooms
that correspond

12:19.939 --> 12:22.374 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
with their official gender at
birth.

12:22.408 --> 12:27.012 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
In last night's debate,
Statehouse members
argued over whether the bill
amounts to discrimination.

12:27.046 --> 12:30.216 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CHRIS PADDIE (R), Texas State
Representative:
There is absolutely no intent,
and I would

12:30.249 --> 12:34.720 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
argue nothing in this language,
that discriminates
against anyone.

12:34.754 --> 12:39.225 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
In fact, it makes sure that
there are reasonable
accommodations for all children.

12:39.258 --> 12:44.063 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
SENFRONIA THOMPSON (D), Texas
State Representative:
Bathrooms, white, colored.

12:44.096 --> 12:52.772 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I was living through that era of
not only
America, but Texas history as
well.

12:52.805 --> 12:55.808 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Bathrooms divided us then, and
it divides
us now.

12:55.841 --> 13:01.547 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: The bill cleared
the Statehouse
today and went to the Senate for
final approval.

13:01.580 --> 13:07.386 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Meanwhile, the Texas legislature
also voted
to let publicly funded foster
care and adoption

13:07.419 --> 13:14.960 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
groups refuse to place adopted
children with
parents who are gay, unmarried
or non-Christian.

13:14.994 --> 13:21.267 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
An elite New Hampshire prep
school has acknowledged
sexual abuse of students by 13
former teachers

13:21.300 --> 13:23.502 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
and staff dating back decades.

13:23.536 --> 13:29.008 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
St. Paul's School in Concord
today released
results of an independent
investigation.

13:29.041 --> 13:33.646 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It comes amid reports of similar
scandals
at several other private
boarding schools

13:33.679 --> 13:36.649 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
across New England and the
Northeast.

13:36.682 --> 13:43.122 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In economic news, Ford Motor
Company replaced
Mark Fields as CEO after just
two years, amid

13:43.155 --> 13:45.925 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
doubts about the automaker's
direction.

13:45.958 --> 13:51.063 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The new CEO is Jim Hackett, a
former office
furniture executive.

13:51.096 --> 13:56.235 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And on Wall Street, the Dow
Jones industrial
average gained 90 points to
close near 20895.

13:56.268 --> 14:02.842 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The Nasdaq rose almost 50, and
the S&amp;P 500
added 12.

14:02.875 --> 14:09.381 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And after 150 years almost, the
Ringling Bros.
Barnum &amp; Bailey Circus held its
final show

14:09.415 --> 14:11.183 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
last night.

14:11.217 --> 14:15.487 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The Greatest Show on Earth faced
declining
attendance and high operating
costs, as well

14:15.521 --> 14:17.957 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
as protests from animal rights
groups.

14:17.990 --> 14:24.029 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The last show on Sunday, held
just outside
New York City, received a
standing ovation.

14:24.063 --> 14:30.135 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Performers hugged, as the
ringmaster sang
"Auld Lang Syne."

14:30.169 --> 14:35.174 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Still to come on the "NewsHour":
President
Trump abroad attempting to reset
relations

14:35.207 --> 14:41.680 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in the Middle East; how Medicaid
cuts could
trickle down to students with
disabilities;

14:41.714 --> 14:46.719 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
it's Politics Monday, a look at
the storm
left at home while the president
is overseas;

14:46.752 --> 14:58.597 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
and much more.

14:58.631 --> 15:03.369 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
During the presidential
campaign, candidate
Trump said he'd strengthen
relations with

15:03.402 --> 15:09.041 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Middle Eastern countries and do
a better job
fighting what he called radical
Islamic terrorism.

15:09.074 --> 15:13.879 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, with the president in Saudi
Arabia this
weekend and meeting with Arab
leaders, we

15:13.913 --> 15:18.584 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
thought we'd ask, what kind of
change in U.S.
policy is the president making?

15:18.617 --> 15:20.419 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
For that, we turn to Daniel
Benjamin.

15:20.452 --> 15:25.491 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He was ambassador at large and
coordinator
for counterterrorism at the U.S.
State Department

15:25.524 --> 15:27.493 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
during the Obama administration.

15:27.526 --> 15:29.828 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
He's now at Dartmouth College.

15:29.862 --> 15:33.966 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Elliott Abrams, he served in the
Reagan and
George W. Bush administrations.

15:33.999 --> 15:37.469 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He's now a senior fellow at the
Council on
Foreign Relations.

15:37.503 --> 15:42.474 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And Robin Wright, she is a
fellow at the U.S.
Institute of Peace, as well as a
contributing

15:42.508 --> 15:45.010 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
writer for "The New Yorker"
magazine.

15:45.044 --> 15:47.179 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And we welcome all three of you
back to the
program.

15:47.212 --> 15:51.216 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, we have been talking about
-- a little
bit, Elliott Abrams, about the
president's

15:51.250 --> 15:55.421 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
shifting language in how he
talks about terrorism,
extremism.

15:55.454 --> 16:00.793 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But what I want to ask the three
of you is,
how much of a shift in policy is
what Donald

16:00.826 --> 16:06.932 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
-- President Trump is saying in
his -- particularly
in that speech in Saudi Arabia?

16:06.966 --> 16:08.801 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
How much of a shift in policy
would that be?

16:08.834 --> 16:11.537 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ELLIOTT ABRAMS, Council on
Foreign Relations:
There is a shift, I would say,
from the Obama

16:11.570 --> 16:19.111 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
policy, which was much more open
to friendship
or a better relationship with
Iran and wasn't

16:19.144 --> 16:23.215 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
casting Iran as a central
problem in the Middle
East.

16:23.248 --> 16:28.220 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
In Saudi Arabia, the president
said very much
Iran is the problem.

16:28.253 --> 16:32.691 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The king of Saudi Arabia then
said the same
thing, Iran is the problem.

16:32.725 --> 16:35.828 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Now, of course, we're hearing it
from Prime
Minister Netanyahu.

16:35.861 --> 16:41.700 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This isn't a change, I would
say, from Bush
policy, actually, but it is a
change from

16:41.734 --> 16:45.571 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Obama policy, which was centered
on improving
the relationship with Iran.

16:45.604 --> 16:49.508 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Daniel Benjamin,
how do you
see what the president had to
say?

16:49.541 --> 16:52.678 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DANIEL BENJAMIN, Former State
Department Coordinator
for Counterterrorism: Well, I
agree with Elliott

16:52.711 --> 16:56.515 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
about the tilt towards the Sunni
Arabs.

16:56.548 --> 17:02.688 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He's gone all in, in terms of
standing with
them and with the Israelis
against Iran.

17:02.721 --> 17:05.691 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I think that brings with it some
challenges.

17:05.724 --> 17:14.099 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think it's also noteworthy
that he pushed
the Saudis and others to do more
against terrorism

17:14.133 --> 17:19.405 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
themselves, but it was quite
interesting that
the way that he described
terrorism, it was

17:19.438 --> 17:21.340 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
really kind of flat.

17:21.373 --> 17:27.479 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It was in very good vs. evil
terms, but no
larger discussion of what the
drivers of terrorism

17:27.513 --> 17:33.886 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
are, no discussion about bad
governance, about
economic stagnation, about any
repression.

17:33.919 --> 17:40.759 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, as a result, it leaves the
impression
that this is going to be purely
about military

17:40.793 --> 17:45.164 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
law enforcement, and not
anything else, which
is really at odds with the
policy we had,

17:45.197 --> 17:47.299 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
which was that you can't shoot
your way out
of this.

17:47.332 --> 17:48.901 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Robin Wright,
you're nodding
your head.

17:48.934 --> 17:50.069 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ROBIN WRIGHT, Senior Fellow,
U.S. Institute
of Peace: Absolutely.

17:50.102 --> 17:52.571 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I think this is -- this differs
in significant
ways.

17:52.604 --> 17:56.875 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
First of all, it walks away from
the kind
of nation-building of George
Bush or the democracy

17:56.909 --> 17:58.877 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
promotion of Barack Obama.

17:58.911 --> 18:03.282 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It takes a very one-dimensional
approach to
extremism, which is
militaristic, kill them

18:03.315 --> 18:05.084 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
all, drive them back.

18:05.117 --> 18:10.255 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It is -- doesn't factor in the
kind of economic
grievances, the political sense
among many

18:10.289 --> 18:13.125 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
in the region that their
governments don't
represent them.

18:13.158 --> 18:17.529 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
President Trump is basically
siding with the
autocratic regimes in the region
which have

18:17.563 --> 18:23.335 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
been the most repressive, and
which have not
devoted much time or energy to
some of the

18:23.368 --> 18:26.004 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
broad solutions of the 21st
century.

18:26.038 --> 18:29.041 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And so this is a huge departure
from the past.

18:29.074 --> 18:34.713 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I think that it opens up the
United States
to some vulnerability in the
same way.

18:34.746 --> 18:39.751 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We're once again looking for
stability, rather
than the kinds of regimes that
reflect our

18:39.785 --> 18:41.320 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
own values.

18:41.353 --> 18:45.057 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Is this an
approach, Elliott
Abrams, that is likely to work?

18:45.090 --> 18:50.429 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
These regimes have had plenty of
opportunities
to come together against
terrorism, against

18:50.462 --> 18:52.364 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
extremism.

18:52.397 --> 18:55.200 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Is this new appeal from
President Trump likely
to bring results?

18:55.234 --> 19:00.506 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ELLIOTT ABRAMS: Well, there can
be better
cooperation, let's say, on
terrorist financing.

19:00.539 --> 19:03.375 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
There can be better cooperation
on the military
and police side.

19:03.408 --> 19:05.444 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
But I think Robin is right.

19:05.477 --> 19:09.982 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
If terrorists were coming down
from outer
space, then the military
approach would be

19:10.015 --> 19:11.483 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
fine.

19:11.517 --> 19:14.019 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But they're coming from the very
countries
whose leaders he was addressing.

19:14.052 --> 19:19.091 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And he didn't discuss at all,
why is that
and what can be done about it in
your countries?

19:19.124 --> 19:24.997 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, given that,
Dan Benjamin,
are we -- are these countries
just basically

19:25.030 --> 19:27.900 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
left to ignore the president?

19:27.933 --> 19:33.138 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I mean, has the expectation been
raised for
them to do something now or not?

19:33.172 --> 19:37.609 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
DANIEL BENJAMIN: Well, he has
suggested that.

19:37.643 --> 19:43.115 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
One of the reasons that the Gulf
Arabs are
so excited about Donald Trump is
that he has

19:43.148 --> 19:46.418 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
signaled that he's giving them a
complete
pass on human rights issues.

19:46.451 --> 19:48.887 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, we could well see more
repression.

19:48.921 --> 19:51.089 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Over the long term, that doesn't
mean less
terrorism.

19:51.123 --> 19:53.692 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
That may mean more terrorism.

19:53.725 --> 19:58.797 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But he's really just saying, you
know, do
what you need to and be there
for us when

19:58.830 --> 20:00.632 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
we ask.

20:00.666 --> 20:05.938 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That's also a problem because,
over the last
five or six years, they have
paid a lot more

20:05.971 --> 20:10.475 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
attention to their sectarian
rivalry with
Iran than they have to Sunni
extremism.

20:10.509 --> 20:17.382 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And speaking of
that, Robin,
that's come up in all of this
discussion.

20:17.416 --> 20:23.422 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Does it make sense in the long
run for the
president to pit basically Sunni
against the

20:23.455 --> 20:24.423 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Iran regime?

20:24.456 --> 20:26.425 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ROBIN WRIGHT: This is the great
danger.

20:26.458 --> 20:31.797 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The United States is often
faulted with fostering
this sectarian divide between
Sunnis and Shiites

20:31.830 --> 20:35.334 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
by its intervention in Iraq in
2003.

20:35.367 --> 20:41.840 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And now the administration is
taking a very
definitive stand on the side of
the Sunnis

20:41.873 --> 20:44.710 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
against predominantly Shiite
Iran.

20:44.743 --> 20:48.847 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And this, I think, is going to
deepen tensions,
rather than try to defuse them.

20:48.880 --> 20:53.785 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the great danger is that you
see not only
tensions within societies that
don't feel

20:53.819 --> 20:56.922 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that they're represented, but a
deepening
regional conflict.

20:56.955 --> 21:03.762 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
After all, the Saudi-Iran
rivalry plays out
in every major conflict in the
Middle East,

21:03.795 --> 21:06.265 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
in Syria, in Iraq, in Yemen.

21:06.298 --> 21:09.968 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And we're not going to find
solution to any
of these crises unless there's a
much more

21:10.002 --> 21:15.073 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
collaborative effort that brings
in all the
major powers in the region.

21:15.107 --> 21:16.908 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
And so that's one of the
challenges.

21:16.942 --> 21:22.948 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He talks a game about finding
peace and about
stabilizing the region, fighting
extremism,

21:22.981 --> 21:27.419 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
but how do you do that when
you're actually
adding fuel to the flames?

21:27.452 --> 21:29.254 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And what about,
Elliott?

21:29.288 --> 21:32.357 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ELLIOTT ABRAMS: Well, there, I
would say I
disagree, because I think the
problem, seen

21:32.391 --> 21:35.827 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
from the Israeli point of view,
seen from
the Sunni Arab point of view,
seen from the

21:35.861 --> 21:42.868 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
president's point of view, is a
remarkable
effort by Iran in Iraq, in
Syria, in Lebanon,

21:42.901 --> 21:46.305 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
in Yemen, in Bahrain, to create
trouble.

21:46.338 --> 21:51.076 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I think they are really a
problem for all
of those countries and for us.

21:51.109 --> 21:53.512 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
This is a country that is still
saying death
to America.

21:53.545 --> 21:56.348 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I think the president's focus on
that is reasonable.

21:56.381 --> 21:59.084 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And, Daniel
Benjamin, pick
up on that.

21:59.117 --> 22:06.024 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What is the meat on the bones
that needs to
come now for something to grow
out of this

22:06.058 --> 22:10.128 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that advances the cause, the
anti-extremist
cause?

22:10.162 --> 22:16.234 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DANIEL BENJAMIN: Well, I'm
skeptical we're
going to get there, because one
of the things

22:16.268 --> 22:21.173 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that President Trump apparently
didn't do
while he was in Saudi Arabia was
talk to the

22:21.206 --> 22:27.312 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Saudis about the activities that
they carry
on that actually promote
extremism, specific

22:27.346 --> 22:32.117 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
with their missionary activities
around the
world to provide mosques,
itinerant preachers,

22:32.150 --> 22:37.789 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
curricular materials and the
like, which have
really stoked the rise of a more
hard-edge

22:37.823 --> 22:39.491 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Islam.

22:39.524 --> 22:42.527 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I don't think we're going to
see anything
from this administration on that
score.

22:42.561 --> 22:48.800 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the other thing is, on the
sectarianism,
if it just gets worse, it's
going to undermine

22:48.834 --> 22:50.068 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
regional stability.

22:50.102 --> 22:53.305 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And it could threaten the
nuclear accord in
the region.

22:53.338 --> 22:55.841 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And that ultimately would be bad
news for
everyone.

22:55.874 --> 23:01.146 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: We even haven't
mentioned the
elections in Iran, Robin, but
Iran has just

23:01.179 --> 23:06.151 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
reelected the more moderate
candidate, Mr.
Rouhani.

23:06.184 --> 23:09.654 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
At the same time, the president
is painting
Iran as the enemy.

23:09.688 --> 23:14.292 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ROBIN WRIGHT: And he's painting
that picture
in a country that doesn't hold
democratic

23:14.326 --> 23:18.930 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
elections, where women can't
even drive, much
less participate or run for
office.

23:18.964 --> 23:21.867 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And Iran has had a female vice
president.

23:21.900 --> 23:23.735 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
The contrast is very stark.

23:23.769 --> 23:27.072 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There's no question that Iran is
a big problem
for many in the international
community, its

23:27.105 --> 23:31.810 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
support of extremism, its
missile development
program, its abuse of civil
rights.

23:31.843 --> 23:33.545 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I don't think anyone disputes
that.

23:33.578 --> 23:35.947 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
But there is a deep contrast.

23:35.981 --> 23:41.386 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And remember that Saudi Arabia
is a country
that developed or promoted the
Wahhabi ideology

23:41.420 --> 23:50.395 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that was the bed of the place
that gave us
the ideology of al-Qaida and
ISIS, and so

23:50.429 --> 23:55.901 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that we need to kind of be
rational or reasonable
when we talk about who are the
good guys and

23:55.934 --> 23:56.902 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
the bad guys.

23:56.935 --> 23:58.270 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
A lot of them share the blame.

23:58.303 --> 24:00.505 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Well, there's so
much here.

24:00.539 --> 24:03.708 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We're going to continue to look
at what the
president had to say.

24:03.742 --> 24:07.546 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Thank you, all three, Robin
Wright, Daniel
Benjamin, Elliott Abrams.

24:07.579 --> 24:08.547 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Thank you.

24:08.580 --> 24:09.848 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
ROBIN WRIGHT: Thank you.

24:09.881 --> 24:17.155 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
ELLIOTT ABRAMS: You're welcome.

24:17.189 --> 24:23.929 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Let's move to the
president's
domestic agenda now.

24:23.962 --> 24:28.800 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Later tonight, his
administration will release
his first full budget plan,
which lays out

24:28.834 --> 24:31.837 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
his priorities for spending and
taxes.

24:31.870 --> 24:36.675 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Congress will have the final
say, but this
lays down an important marker
for the coming

24:36.708 --> 24:38.643 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
year.

24:38.677 --> 24:42.948 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Early reporting suggests Mr.
Trump's proposal
will feature some big changes,
including substantial

24:42.981 --> 24:46.351 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
spending cuts and a shift in
priorities overall.

24:46.384 --> 24:51.223 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Lisa Desjardins has been
reporting for us,
and she is here now to give us a
preview.

24:51.256 --> 24:54.392 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, Lisa, what's different about
this budget
and what is different about the
way they're

24:54.426 --> 24:56.194 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
approaching it?

24:56.228 --> 24:58.797 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: This is a very
dramatic proposal
the president is making to
Congress.

24:58.830 --> 25:04.169 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He would significantly increase
military spending
and significantly decrease most
spending in

25:04.202 --> 25:05.804 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
other domestic agencies.

25:05.837 --> 25:10.408 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now, as part of this, he is
trying to change
the way people look at
budgeting.

25:10.442 --> 25:13.044 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Sources, congressional sources
are giving
me all this information.

25:13.078 --> 25:17.582 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They say he's trying to say,
don't just look
who is the recipient of a
program.

25:17.616 --> 25:22.087 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Look at those who are funding
it, taxpayers,
and ask, do taxpayers think this
is worth

25:22.120 --> 25:23.088 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
it?

25:23.121 --> 25:24.789 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
That's a sign of cuts to come.

25:24.823 --> 25:28.159 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And we're hearing
big changes
to Medicaid, health care for the
poor.

25:28.193 --> 25:29.961 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
What do we know about that?

25:29.995 --> 25:32.831 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
LISA DESJARDINS: These
congressional sources
say the president will propose
additional

25:32.864 --> 25:37.836 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
cuts to Medicaid on top of what
is already
in the House Republican bill.

25:37.869 --> 25:40.505 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We have talked about that
extensively.

25:40.539 --> 25:43.441 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There's a lot of shifts in that
bill, but
essentially it would likely
mean, according

25:43.475 --> 25:47.979 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to the Congressional Budget
Office, millions
fewer Americans on Medicaid.

25:48.013 --> 25:51.449 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The president plan would have
additional decreases
to that.

25:51.483 --> 25:55.887 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And, finally,
Lisa, we're hearing
about several other changes to
the so-called

25:55.921 --> 25:57.289 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
social safety net.

25:57.322 --> 25:58.557 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: That's right.

25:58.590 --> 26:00.158 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: What are you
hearing about
that and why?

26:00.191 --> 26:03.128 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: A couple of big
programs
to watch, the Earned Income Tax
Credit.

26:03.161 --> 26:07.132 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Again, congressional sources say
the president
feels that there should be more
responsibility,

26:07.165 --> 26:12.003 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
accountability in these
programs, and he's
going to require that everyone
in that program

26:12.037 --> 26:13.738 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
have a Social Security number.

26:13.772 --> 26:15.106 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Who does that affect?

26:15.140 --> 26:16.408 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Undocumented immigrants.

26:16.441 --> 26:19.444 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It could also affect their
children, some
critics point out.

26:19.477 --> 26:23.315 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
One other program, Judy, SNAP,
lots of times
referred to as food stamps.

26:23.348 --> 26:28.320 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The president is going to
propose that states
share more in that cost.

26:28.353 --> 26:30.088 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
That would be a big difference.

26:30.121 --> 26:33.658 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And one key to all of this, it's
a dramatic
proposal, but Congress ends up
deciding all

26:33.692 --> 26:35.527 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
of these funding debates.

26:35.560 --> 26:38.597 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And when I talk to some
Republicans in Congress
on Friday, they were ready for
this dramatic

26:38.630 --> 26:39.831 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
proposal.

26:39.864 --> 26:42.300 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And they said a lot of these
cuts will not
pass there.

26:42.334 --> 26:45.604 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: All right, Lisa
Desjardins,
again, this comes out tonight.

26:45.637 --> 26:47.572 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We will be able to talk much
more about it
tomorrow.

26:47.606 --> 26:49.341 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Thank you so much.

26:49.374 --> 26:55.180 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, as we just heard, Medicaid
cuts are a
key part of the president's
proposed budget.

26:55.213 --> 27:00.485 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Mr. Trump's budget assumes that
cuts already
in the House Republican health
care bill will

27:00.518 --> 27:03.288 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
eventually become law and take
effect.

27:03.321 --> 27:05.991 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We have been looking at the
potential impact
of the bill.

27:06.024 --> 27:11.630 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, tonight, we focus on what
it could mean
for schools, and particularly
special education.

27:11.663 --> 27:13.598 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
William Brangham has our
conversation.

27:13.632 --> 27:17.435 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Special
education just wasn't
part of the debate over the
House GOP's health

27:17.469 --> 27:19.237 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
care bill.

27:19.270 --> 27:23.141 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But special education is hugely
reliant on
Medicaid , and that bill could
trigger major

27:23.174 --> 27:27.545 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
cuts to Medicaid, up to $880
billion over
10 years.

27:27.579 --> 27:31.416 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, what would this mean for the
millions
of public school kids who
receive special

27:31.449 --> 27:33.184 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
ed services?

27:33.218 --> 27:37.288 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
I'm joined now by Sasha
Pudelski, who is with
the School Superintendents
Association.

27:37.322 --> 27:38.623 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Welcome to the "NewsHour."

27:38.657 --> 27:39.290 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
SASHA PUDELSKI, The School
Superintendents
Association: Thanks.

27:39.324 --> 27:40.425 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
So happy to be here.

27:40.458 --> 27:41.960 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: So, I was
really surprised
by this.

27:41.993 --> 27:46.064 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I didn't appreciate fully how
reliant special
ed service are on Medicaid.

27:46.097 --> 27:49.534 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Can you give us a sense of how
crucial they
are to those budgets?

27:49.567 --> 27:50.669 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
SASHA PUDELSKI: Absolutely.

27:50.702 --> 27:53.905 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, special education funding
has always been
low.

27:53.938 --> 27:58.576 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We have never met our federal
commitment to
school districts to fund special
education.

27:58.610 --> 28:03.114 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And about 30 years ago, the
federal government
decided that they would allow to
start to

28:03.148 --> 28:08.286 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
bill Medicaid for some of the
therapies in
particular that are very costly
to provide

28:08.319 --> 28:10.088 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
special education students.

28:10.121 --> 28:13.658 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so school districts have
been reliant
on Medicaid to supplement some
of the special

28:13.692 --> 28:16.494 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
education funding they receive
for a very
long time.

28:16.528 --> 28:18.029 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It's standard practice in many
districts.

28:18.063 --> 28:19.464 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: So, they spend
this money.

28:19.497 --> 28:21.833 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
And then they go to the
government say, hey,
we did this.

28:21.866 --> 28:22.834 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
We provided these services.

28:22.867 --> 28:23.868 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Please reimburse us.

28:23.902 --> 28:25.737 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
SASHA PUDELSKI: Exactly.

28:25.770 --> 28:28.073 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, it's not a one-for-one
match, by any means,
but it's a substantial amount
they receive

28:28.106 --> 28:29.874 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
back.

28:29.908 --> 28:32.010 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Generally
speaking, who
are the kids that we're talking
about here,

28:32.043 --> 28:34.079 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and what kinds of services are
we talking
about?

28:34.112 --> 28:38.516 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SASHA PUDELSKI: It's virtually
every special
education child, because the
things that Medicaid

28:38.550 --> 28:44.322 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
can cover run from therapies
like mental health
therapy, speech therapy,
physical therapy,

28:44.355 --> 28:48.393 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to equipment that they may need,
hearing aids.

28:48.426 --> 28:54.332 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It may run from wheelchairs to
school buses,
actually, that provide
specialized transportation

28:54.365 --> 28:55.600 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
for kids.

28:55.633 --> 28:58.002 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, the services are vast,
despite the levels
of funding.

28:58.036 --> 29:00.305 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: So, we don't
know right
now.

29:00.338 --> 29:02.474 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The House GOP bill has to go
through the Senate.

29:02.507 --> 29:04.242 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's obviously going to get
changed quite
a bit.

29:04.275 --> 29:08.580 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But let's assume that there are
still major
cuts to Medicaid in whatever
comes out of

29:08.613 --> 29:10.181 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
the Congress.

29:10.215 --> 29:12.016 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
What is the main concern for the
school districts?

29:12.050 --> 29:16.621 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SASHA PUDELSKI: The main concern
is, by this
major federal disinvestment in
Medicaid, we're

29:16.654 --> 29:20.325 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
going to have states having to
pick up the
tab.

29:20.358 --> 29:25.797 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And if school districts are
competing with
hospitals and clinics and other
providers

29:25.830 --> 29:30.902 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
for scarce dollars, I don't see
how a governor
or state Medicaid director or
state legislature

29:30.935 --> 29:35.607 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
is going to decide schools need
this money,
not a hospital, not a doctor.

29:35.640 --> 29:41.045 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: The
Republicans would argue,
we have federal deficits that
are going to

29:41.079 --> 29:45.683 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
be massive in the future, and we
have to address
some of these programs like
Medicaid, and

29:45.717 --> 29:48.453 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that these are cuts that are
just fiscally
smart.

29:48.486 --> 29:50.388 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I mean, how do you respond to
that?

29:50.421 --> 29:53.892 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SASHA PUDELSKI: It's not kids
that are breaking
the Medicaid bank, if the bank
is even being

29:53.925 --> 29:55.760 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
broken, which I contend it's
not.

29:55.794 --> 30:02.167 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
But when you look at who
benefits from Medicaid,
46 percent of Medicaid
beneficiaries are kids.

30:02.200 --> 30:06.504 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But one out of every five
dollars spent on
Medicaid is spent on children.

30:06.538 --> 30:10.842 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So it's a really efficient way
of spending
dollars on children's health
care in this

30:10.875 --> 30:12.644 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
country.

30:12.677 --> 30:15.480 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Let's say
these cuts do
come down, and school districts
have to find

30:15.513 --> 30:17.081 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
some way to compensate.

30:17.115 --> 30:19.551 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What is your sense, from talking
to school
administrators around the
country?

30:19.584 --> 30:20.885 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
How are they going to make up
the shortfall?

30:20.919 --> 30:23.288 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
SASHA PUDELSKI: So, the
situation is rather
bleak.

30:23.321 --> 30:29.127 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We surveyed 1,000 school leaders
earlier this
year to ask them exactly that
question.

30:29.160 --> 30:33.298 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And they told us that they
believe services
for kids will be recused.

30:33.331 --> 30:37.335 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In some cases, professionals
will be laid
off who work with those kids,
like the school

30:37.368 --> 30:41.639 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
nurse, for example, whose salary
may be subsidized
substantially by Medicaid.

30:41.673 --> 30:46.544 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They indicated they may have to
raise taxes
in order to compensate for this
loss.

30:46.578 --> 30:48.913 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And some districts can do that,
and others
just can't.

30:48.947 --> 30:52.784 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, it's going to be a major
financial hit,
not just on the special
education budget,

30:52.817 --> 30:56.988 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
but on the general education
budget, because
the general education budget
will have to

30:57.021 --> 30:59.824 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
subsidize the loss of funding in
special education.

